This developmental task will require students to apply their fitness and training knowledge. This includes the muscular system, fitness components and training methods.&nbsp;<br />
<br />
&nbsp;

The Year 9 curriculum supports students to critique the effectiveness of strategies to enhance health, fitness and wellbeing. To demonstrate this knowledge in a written test, students will use their practical experience and fitness and training concepts learnt throughout Term 2.<br />
<br />
&nbsp;

The DEV task for the Dystopian writing CAT requires you to build your own dystopia. In doing so you will think about different dystopian characteristics and themes you will explore, the power dynamics of the world, and the people, environment, and history that make it up. You will additionally write a short scene detailing a &#39;Day in the Life&#39; of the everyday citizen in this society.&nbsp;<br />
<br />
This task will help consolidate your understanding of dystopian features. While the CAT gives you the option to write on a gap/silence from a mentor text, if you decide to write an original dystopian story (Subject to conversation with your teacher), you can use this world as a base.&nbsp;

Students will view the film &#39;The Truman Show&#39; and explore themes, characters, plot and the construction of film as text, in particular the importance of mise-en-scene. Once students have completed this in-depth study, they will be required to examine a series of still shots and analyse these in accordance to their study of film components from The Truman Show by producing a written analysis.&nbsp;<br />
<br />
